article.headline: Indiana 83, Seattle 77
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Seattle Storm coach Anne Donovan was more
impressed with Lauren Jackson's defense than her double-double.

Jackson had 24 points, 15 rebounds, five blocked shots and
controlled the paint during Seattle's 83-77 victory over the
Indiana Fever on Saturday night.

"Defensively, she's such a presence," Donovan said. "She has
been so active this year. I don't think in the past she took this
much pride in her defense. Now she's being a stopper."

The Storm (4-1) won their fourth straight game since an 18-point
loss to Los Angeles in the season opener. Jackson scored eight
points in that game, and has averaged 18 points since.

"We emphasize defense, and we did well," Jackson said. "We
played good defense."

Sue Bird scored 20 points, Janell Burse had 15 and Betty Lennox
added 13 for the Storm.

The Fever (4-2) have lost two of their last three games and
remain winless in five trips to Seattle.

"We only lost by six, and they shot 37 free throws compared to
our 17," the Fever's Tamika Catchings said. "That's a 20-point
deficit. You take away 20 points, we win the game by 14."

The Storm were whistled for 16 fouls, while the Fever had 28.

A 3-pointer by Tan White gave Indiana its first lead at 41-40
with 15:30 to play in the game. Seattle responded and outscored
Indiana 32-18 over the next 11 minutes to gain control.

The Fever played without starting point Tully Bevilaqua, who won
the WNBA title with Seattle last year. Bevilaqua is out with a
sprained knee, but did receive her championship ring before the
game.

"I think we played well out of the gate," said Indiana head
coach Brian Winter. "Unfortunately, Tully (Bevilaqua) got hurt and
that's hurt us. We have to make an adjustment now and that's never
easy to do."

White, the second overall pick in the April's WNBA Draft,
stepped in and played impressively in her first start. White led
all scorers with 26 points. Kelly Miller had 19. Tamika Catchings
struggled and scored 12 points on 3 of 16 shooting.

"Tan came in and gave us some huge shots down the stretch,"
Catchings said. "That's what we need, especially when I'm shooting
as bad as that. It's great to see other people step up."

The Storm got off to a strong start, making 6 of their first 7
shots from the field en route to a 15-4 lead 3:30 into the game.

"We got off to another quick start. We always seem to do
that," Jackson said.

Catchings missed her first five shots and failed to hit a field
goal until the a minute remained in the half.

Seattle led by as much as 10 twice in the first half, but
Indiana scored the final five points before the break, cutting the
Storm's lead to 35-30.
